Hedge funds dive 
				into distressed debt

May 18, 2006





From 
				Global Investor:

Hedge funds 
				investing in distressed funds that are in liquidation has grown 
				significantly in the past two years, mainly due to the increase 
				in the capital managed by hedge funds and the number of 
				distressed opportunities, according to research by Walkers, a 
				global law firm.

				Distressed funds have not had many opportunities, seeing as 
				traditional banks don't like to lend money to fund liquidations. 
				Typically, they only lend when there is an assurance that the 
				borrower can make good on his or her loan. However, hedge funds 
				have demonstrated a willing to finance such liquidations because 
				of the potential for high returns.




