Texas Pacific forms venture to raise distressed securities fund

February 23, 2006





From 
				Bloomberg News:

Texas Pacific Group, 
				the buyout firm that owns stakes in Burger King Corp. and 
				China's Lenovo Group Ltd., formed a venture to invest in 
				securities of troubled companies, a person familiar with the 
				matter said.

				The firm started Minneapolis-based TPG Credit Management LP with 
				former Cargill Inc. executive Rory O'Neill, 41. The venture 
				plans to raise less than $1 billion, said the person, who 
				declined to be identified because O'Neill is seeking investors 
				for the private fund.

				Texas Pacific, based in Forth Worth, is following rivals Carlyle 
				Group and Blackstone Group LP into the distressed fund market, 
				where investors bet that securities of companies will rise in 
				value as they emerge from bankruptcy or restructuring. Moody's 
				Investors Service expects the rate of defaults for high-yield 
				bonds to climb by year-end to 3.3 percent from 1.9 percent in 
				January. 




